      <bioghist id="aspace_5ad56646fdc0c0b8e04d7eb5ebf99f55">
         <head>Thomas Osbert Mordaunt (1730-1809)</head>
         <p>Thomas Osbert Mordaunt, a British military officer, was born in London, the son of Colonel Charles Mordaunt (-1762) and his second wife Ann Howe Mordaunt (-1753); she was the daughter of Scrope Howe (1648-1713) and the aunt to two noted British military officers, Admiral Richard Howe (1726-1799) and General William Howe (1729-1814), the sons of her brother Emanuel Scrope Howe (1698-1735). Mordaunt's grandfather was Brigadier-General Lewis Mordaunt (1665-1712/13).</p>
         <p>Mordaunt had a career in the Army, and was known for his heroic actions with the 10th Dragoons during the Seven Years War. In the Battle of Warburg (July 31, 1760), after a second volley on the field, he, as a captain, was the single officer remaining alive and rallied his squadron to capture 300 German prisoners, ammunition, wagons of stores, and two cannon. He eventually rose to the rank of major general and retired in 1787. Mordaunt was elected a Fellow of the Society of Antiquaries in 1796. In retirement he was living for most of the year at Margate while keeping his London residence in St. James's Place. He died on February 13, 1809 and was buried at All Saints Church, Fulham.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_6060a13d5b1d44850ad474b43c365aa5">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Thomas Osbert Mordaunt Correspondence. The Lewis Walpole Library, Yale University.</p>
      </prefercite>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_c089601ee9dcf235827d0fb96607b2cc">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The Thomas Osbert Mordaunt Correspondence contains more than seventy letters received by the retired Army general at his homes in London and Margate. The letters are from friends, relatives, and former military colleagues who relayed personal news and that of mutual acquaintances and family members, as well as social gossip, political news, and other items they felt would be of interest and entertainment. While the letters are primarily from friends and include groups of letters from three women, the collection also includes some military-related and financial material, including records of a land sale that Mordaunt made.</p>
         <p>Of note are the number of letters he received from two women in the family of his cousin Admiral Richard Howe: his daughter Baroness Sophia Charlotte Howe (1762-1835) and her aunt Catherine Hartopp Heywood (1728-1807), the sister of Howe's wife Mary. Baroness Howe sent twenty-four letters and Mrs. Heywood a dozen, all friendly and carrying news of family, events, politics, and society meant to keep their retired friend up-to-date on their activities as well as to express their concern for his welfare.</p>
         <p>Literary friends present in the collection are a fellow fossil collector Eliza (or Elizabeth) Sotheby (1751-1827) and the clergyman/poet John Delap (1725-1812), with a half-dozen letters each. Delap also wrote out a verse he had composed for the marriage of Lady Mary Henrietta Julia Osborne (1776-1862) to his friend Thomas Pelham, Earl Chichester (1756-1826), on July 16, 1801.</p>
         <p>Land and financial transactions are recorded in the letters from Charles Butler, solicitors Thomas and William Dunn, and the agriculturist Thomas Eccleston, regarding Mordaunt's sale of the manors of Downholland and Halsal to Eccleston. Mordaunt's military friend J. C. Pleydell sent information on Fort Kehl and a watercolor map of the area; the fort, set on an island in the Rhine River between Kehl and Strasbourg, had been the site of the recent Battle of Kehl (June 23-24, 1796). In the same letter he related his visit to the studio of John Flaxman to check on a sculpture of a faun commissioned by Mordaunt, and while there saw the memorials for Sir William Jones, Sir Robert Ladbroke, and David Murray, Lord Mansfield, in progress. In a second letter he wrote of having just seen from his window the French aeronaut André-Jacques Garnerin's flight in a hydrogen balloon.</p>
      </scopecontent>
