               <bioghist id="aspace_1ad81a1fad93fd4dcdeef5a679af3bee">
                  <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
                  <p>Catherine Heywood was the first of two daughters born to Major Chiverton Hartopp (1690-1759) and Catherine Mansfield Hartopp (1711-1755); her sister Mary was the wife of Admiral Richard Howe. In 1754 she married James Modyford Heywood (1732-1798) of Maristow House in Bickleigh, near Plymouth in Devon, who also owned a plantation in Jamaica. The couple had four daughters: Francis (married Thomas Orby Hunter in 1796); Maria Henrietta (married Lewis Montolieu in 1786); Emma (married Admiral Sir Albemarle Bertie in 1782), and Sophia (married Sir John Musters in 1776).</p>
               </bioghist>
               <scopecontent id="aspace_5f91d4634d290587ff9af69e5072fa2a">
                  <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                  <p>Catherine Heywood's twelve letters, mostly written from her home on Bruton Street in London, feature comments on her family and travels, social and political news, and fear of the French invading England. Her concern extended to General Mordaunt, and she regularly encouraged him to leave Margate and come to London for his own safety. Several of her letters discuss her daughter Emma, whose marriage to Admiral Bertie was troublesome for both women.</p>
               </scopecontent>
            </c>
