               <bioghist id="aspace_1c225184576a92cd3e125db5953f358d">
                  <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
                  <p>Elizabeth (or Eliza) Sotheby was the second of five children of Colonel William Sotheby (1688-1766) and Elizabeth Sloane Sotheby (1725-); her younger brother was the poet and translator William Sotheby (1757-1823). A poet herself, her only known published work was <title>
                        <part>Patient Griselda, a Tale, from the Italian of Bocaccio</part>
                     </title> (London, 1798).</p>
               </bioghist>
               <scopecontent id="aspace_5b1e5aaecb60eebb640ce820b8971b2d">
                  <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                  <p>Writing from her homes near Abergavenny, Wales, or on Sion Hill in Clifton, Bristol, Sotheby addressed Mordaunt in London and Margate, and encouraged him to visit. She recalled their times together in Clifton and their shared love of fossils, and sent news of her brother and sister.</p>
               </scopecontent>
            </c>
